						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Celius wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Lazycow wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Just add more challenges, e.g. enemies</div><br /><br />It could also be that the levels are too short, which can really suck in terms of programming if your max number of screens is too low. Depending on &quot;why&quot; the maximum is what it is, you may have to go back and make a lot of changes to the engine to accommodate a larger number of screens.</div><br />The number of screens shouldn't really be a problem, if the gameplay difficulty is well balanced.<br /><br />A small arcade-styled NES game I was recently commissioned to program, cranked up the difficulty with regenerating powerups (like the fruit in Pacman), and some enemies would beeline for them, to give them an advantage over the player.<br /><br />Imagine the hammer in Donkey Kong, being wielded by a common enemy! <img src="./images/smilies/icon_twisted.gif" alt=":twisted:" title="Twisted Evil" /></div>

